DESCRIPTION
  The set builtin enables a shell option named by a single letter after a minus
  or by its long name after -o, and disables it with a plus, and rebinds the
  positional parameters to its operands after a double dash or the first
  non-option word. With no argument it lists the shell variables. The OPTION
  SWITCHES section below describes every switch letter and every long name -o
  and +o accept, and -p prints the same table with each option's current state.

SYNOPSIS
  set [-aAbBCeEfGhIkmMnSTuvWx] [+aAbBCeEfGhIkmMnSTuvWx] [-o name] [+o name] [-p] [--] [arg ...]

OPTIONS
      --help              Display help.
  -M, --mood=<...>        Set the runtime mood to shit, bash, or sh, or print it
                          with no value.
  -L, --init-moods=<.., ..>
                          Source the startup files for the listed moods, or
                          print the loaded ones with no value.
OPTION SWITCHES
  A letter after a minus enables the option and after a plus disables it.
  -o NAME and +o NAME do the same by long name.

  -e  errexit, error-exit           Exit on the first command that fails.
  -x  xtrace                        Print each command after expansion before it runs.
  -u  nounset, no-unset             Treat an unset variable as an error.
      pipefail                      Report a pipeline's status as the rightmost stage that failed.
  -a  allexport, export-all         Mark every assigned variable for the environment.
  -C  noclobber, no-clobber         Refuse to overwrite an existing file through '>'.
  -f  noglob, no-glob               Disable pathname expansion.
  -n  noexec, no-exec               Read and parse commands but do not run them.
      shitbox                       Resolve the bundled shitbox utility names directly as commands.
  -m  monitor                       Run background jobs in their own process group with notifications.
      failglob                      Fail a command whose glob matches nothing.
  -b  notify                        Report a background job's completion immediately when it finishes.
      vi                            Use vi-style command-line editing.
      emacs                         Use emacs-style command-line editing, the default.
  -h  hashall                       Accepted without effect.
  -v  verbose                       Write input to standard error as it is read, the -v flag.
  -k  keyword                       Accepted without effect.
  -T  functrace                     Accepted without effect.
  -B  braceexpand                   Accepted without effect.
  -A  show-ast                      Print the AST before each command runs.
  -R  show-lexed-words              Print the escape bitmap after each parse.
  -E  show-exit-code                Print the exit code after each command.
  -W  force-warnings                Report a strict runtime error as a warning and let the run proceed, the -W flag.
  -I  mimicry                       Mimic the shell a script's shebang names, the -I flag.
      force-diagnostics             Run the analysis stage before each chunk, the inverse of no-diagnostics.
  -S  show-stats                    Print evaluation statistics after each run.
      no-diagnostics                Skip the analysis stage before each chunk runs.
  -G  show-memory                   Print a granular memory report at exit, the --show-memory flag.
      login                         Whether the shell started as a login shell, fixed at startup.
      rcfile                        Whether a custom rc file was named at startup, fixed at startup.

  The -o long names:
    errexit, error-exit, xtrace, nounset, no-unset, pipefail, allexport,
    export-all, noclobber, no-clobber, noglob, no-glob, noexec, no-exec,
    shitbox, monitor, failglob, notify, vi, emacs, hashall, verbose, keyword,
    functrace, braceexpand, show-ast, show-lexed-words, show-exit-code,
    force-warnings, mimicry, force-diagnostics, show-stats, no-diagnostics,
    show-memory, login, rcfile

rc=0
